One of the studies which Rubin et al. reviewed, known as the Essex study, received some criticism for its methodology and analysis, and the authors responded in full to these initial criticisms.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2008-02-01|title=Sensitivity to Mobile Phone Base Station Signals|journal=Environmental Health Perspectives|volume=116|issue=2|pages=A63–4; author reply A64–5|pmc=2235218|pmid=18288297|last1=Cohen|first1=A|last2=Carlo|first2=G|last3=Davidson|first3=A|last4=White|first4=M|last5=Geoghan|first5=C|last6=Goldsworthy|first6=A|last7=Johansson|first7=O|last8=Maisch|first8=D|last9=O'Connor|first9=E|doi=10.1289/ehp.10870}}</ref> The authors noted that their study says nothing about the long-term effects of exposure to electromagnetic fields, but those affected generally claimed to respond to the fields within a few minutes.

