In 2008, another systematic review reached the same conclusion as Rubin et al.<ref name=Roosli2008>{{Cite journal|author=Röösli M |title=Radiofrequency electromagnetic field exposure and non-specific symptoms of ill health: a systematic review |journal=Environ. Res. |volume=107 |issue=2 |pages=277–87 |year=2008 |month=June |pmid=18359015 |doi=10.1016/j.envres.2008.02.003 |url=}}</ref>

A 2005 report by the UK [[Health Protection Agency]] concluded that electromagnetic hypersensitivity needs to be considered in ways other than its [[etiology]]; that is, the suffering is real, even if the underlying cause is not thought to be related to electromagnetic fields. They also wrote that considering only whether electromagnetic radiation was a causative factor was not meeting the needs of sufferers, although continued research on etiology was essential.<ref name=irvine2005 />

In 2002, some controversy over the causal relationship was demonstrated by the Freiburger Appeal, a petition originated by the German environmental medical lobby group [[IGUMED]], which stated that "we can see a clear temporal and spatial correlation between the appearance of [certain] disease and exposure to pulsed high-frequency microwave radiation", and demanding radical restrictions on mobile phone use.<ref name=freiburger>Original text:{{Cite web|url= http://www.igumed.de/apell.html|title= Betreff: Mobilfunk - Freiburger Appell|accessdate=2008-02-06|date= 2002-10-09|language= German|publisher= Interisziplinäre Gesellschaft für Umweltmedezin (IGUMED)}} Translation: {{Cite web|url= http://www.emrnetwork.org/news/IGUMED_english.pdf|title= Freiburger Appeal|accessdate=2008-02-06|date= 2002-10-09|format= PDF|publisher= IGUMED |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070930041008/http://www.emrnetwork.org/news/IGUMED_english.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-09-30}}</ref> To address some of these concerns, and others, Hocking advised in a 2006 WHO proceedings that the test type and duration should be tailored to the individual, and that washout times are needed to prevent a carry-over effect of previous exposure.<ref>{{Cite web
